0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">Family of three hash functions: rapidhash, rapidhashMicro and rapidhashNano</p>
<p dir="auto">Used by <a href="https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5667077" rel="nofollow">Chromium</a>, <a href="https://github.com/facebook/folly/blob/main/folly/container/HeterogeneousAccess.h#L130">Folly's F14</a>, <a href="https://github.com/ninja-build/ninja/blob/656412538b6fc102b809a61e0efce422e5a20534/src/build_log.cc#L61">Ninja</a>, <a href="https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/blob/309b1b158f59485772d5f5fe0a762f20185cf799/base/hashing.jl#L281">JuliaLang</a>, <a href="https://github.com/ziglang/zig/pull/22085" data-hovercard-type="pull_request" data-hovercard-url="/ziglang/zig/pull/22085/hovercard">ziglang</a>, <a href="https://github.com/facebook/fb303/blob/6c0666c96b7112be2cb5608385063f1aed19c43f/fb303/ThreadCachedServiceData.h#L461">fb303</a>, among others</p>
<p dir="auto"><strong>Rapidhash</strong><br>
General purpose hash function, amazing performance across all sizes.<br>
Surpasses <a href="https://github.com/Nicoshev/rapidhash/tree/master?tab=readme-ov-file#outstanding-performance">70GB/s</a> on Apple's M4 cpus.<br>
Clang-18+ compiles it to ~185 instructions, both on x86-64 and aarch64.<br>
The fastest recommended hash function by <a href="https://github.com/rurban/smhasher?tab=readme-ov-file#summary">SMHasher</a> and <a href="https://gitlab.com/fwojcik/smhasher3/-/blob/main/results/README.md#passing-hashes" rel="nofollow">SMHasher3</a>.</p>
<p dir="auto"><strong>RapidhashMicro</strong><br>
Designed for HPC and server applications, where cache misses make a noticeable performance detriment.<br>
Clang-18+ compiles it to ~140 instructions without stack usage, both on x86-64 and aarch64.<br>
Faster for sizes up to 512 bytes, just 15%-20% slower for inputs above 1kb.<br>
Produces same output as Rapidhash for inputs up to 80 bytes.</p>
<p dir="auto"><strong>RapidhashNano</strong><br>
Designed for Mobile and embedded applications, where keeping a small code size is a top priority.<br>
Clang-18+ compiles it to less than 100 instructions without stack usage, both on x86-64 and aarch64.<br>
The fastest for sizes up to 48 bytes, but may be considerably slower for larger inputs.<br>
Produces same output as Rapidhash for inputs up to 48 bytes.</p>
<p dir="auto"><strong>Streamable</strong><br>
The three functions can be computed without knowing the input length upfront.</p>
<p dir="auto"><strong>Universal</strong><br>
All functions have been optimized for both AMD64 and AArch64 systems.<br>
Compatible with gcc, clang, icx and MSVC.<br>
They do not use machine-specific vectorized or cryptographic instruction sets.</p>
<p dir="auto"><strong>Excellent</strong><br>
All functions pass all tests in both <a href="https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/blob/master/doc/rapidhash.txt">SMHasher</a> and <a href="https://gitlab.com/fwojcik/smhasher3/-/blob/main/results/raw/rapidhash.txt" rel="nofollow">SMHasher3</a>.<br>
<a href="https://github.com/Nicoshev/rapidhash/tree/master?tab=readme-ov-file#collision-based-hash-quality-study">Collision-based study</a> showed a collision probability close to ideal.<br>
Outstanding collision ratio when tested with datasets of 16B and 67B keys:</p>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Collision-based hash quality study</h2><a id="user-content-collision-based-hash-quality-study" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: Collision-based hash quality study" href="#collision-based-hash-quality-study"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">A perfect hash function distributes its domain uniformly onto the image.<br>
When the domain's cardinality is a multiple of the image's cardinality, each potential output has the same probability of being produced.<br>
A function producing 64-bit hashes should have a <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$p=1/2^{64}$</math-renderer> of generating each output.</p>
<p dir="auto">If we compute <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$n$</math-renderer> hashes, the expected amount of collisions should be the number of unique input pairs times the probability of producing a given hash.<br>
This should be <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$(n*(n-1))/2 * 1/2^{64}$</math-renderer>, or simplified: <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$(n*(n-1))/2^{65}$</math-renderer>.<br>
In the case of hashing <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$15*2^{30}$</math-renderer> (~16.1B) different keys, we should expect to see <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$7.03$</math-renderer> collisions.</p>
<p dir="auto">We present an experiment in which we use rapidhash to hash <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$68$</math-renderer> datasets of <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$15*2^{30}$</math-renderer> (15Gi) keys each.<br>
For each dataset, the amount of collisions produced is recorded as measurement.<br>
Ideally, the average among measurements should be <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$7.03$</math-renderer> and the results collection should be a binomial distribution.<br>
We obtained a mean value of <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$7.60$</math-renderer>, just <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$8.11$</math-renderer>% over <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$7.03$</math-renderer>.<br>
Each dataset individual result and the collisions test program can be found in the <a href="https://github.com/Nicoshev/rapidhash/tree/master/collisions">collisions folder</a>.<br>
The default seed <math-renderer class="js-inline-math" style="display: inline-block" data-run-id="d521e011c0ce9854a11151e89b33c800">$0$</math-renderer> was used in all experiments.</p>
<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Ports</h2><a id="user-content-ports" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: Ports" href="#ports"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
